{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"63142ee8-5e04-4a74-a725-8ad595ed3f94","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. MAUI has no concept of an HTTP request, so a \"scope\" is effectively the **entire app lifetime** — making `AddScoped` behave like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext is never disposed or replaced.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance every time it's injected.\n2. **Use a DbContext factory:**\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n3. **Manually create scopes** with `IServiceScopeFactory` if you need scoped behavior tied to a page navigation.\n\nThe factory approach (#2) is generally recommended — it gives you explicit control over DbContext lifetime and avoids stale data and memory leaks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d996799e-3bf6-4301-b382-c3f38e52345c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. But in MAUI, there's no \"request\" — the app is a single long-running process. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"9BC0:21A8FE:61EBCFB:6D2B1E4:69EC10A8"},"id":"28628869-0218-44fd-844c-9f064bbc921b","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:54:09.798Z","parentId":"9d3d506b-f3fd-4846-8e8c-e06b7e6a66a3"}
